  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verify customer identities\n- Assess customer risk profiles\n- Conduct background checks\n- Monitor suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- File Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Report large cash transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Develop internal policies and procedures\n- Implement transaction monitoring systems\n- Conduct regular risk assessments\n- Train employees on AML regulations\n\n4. Regulatory Compliance\n- Follow Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Adhere to Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Comply with international anti-money laundering standards\n\n5. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminal financial activities and protect the global financial system's integrity.",
